## Flow

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    Branch[Branch from next]
    Commit[Commit changes]
    Push[Push branch]
    AskPR{Ask user: create PR?}
    CreatePR[gh pr create]
    Merge[gh pr merge]
    CI[CI in next.yml]
    Deploy[Deploy Fly]
    VT[Version sync + tag + GitHub release]

    Branch --> Commit --> Push --> AskPR
    AskPR -->|Yes| CreatePR --> Merge
    Merge --> CI --> Deploy --> VT
```

**Developer flow:**
1. Branch from `next`, make changes, commit, push.
2. **Ask the user** if they want to create a PR. Only create when confirmed.
3. `gh pr create` → open PR targeting `next`.
4. CI runs (Lint & Format + Build). **Both must pass** before merge.
5. **Ask the user** if they want to merge. Only merge when confirmed.
6. `gh pr merge --rebase` → merge into `next`.

**CI flow (after merge to `next`):** A single workflow **`.github/workflows/next.yml`** runs in order:

1. **Lint & Format + Build** — same checks as PR CI (Biome, distros, Docker) on non-`[release]` commits only.
2. **Deploy sync + Deploy app** — Fly deploy after CI succeeds (or on `[release]` / `workflow_dispatch` when CI is skipped by design).
3. **Version tag & release** — only after both deploys succeed, on non-`[release]` pushes: generate version, `bun run version:sync`, commit `[release] …`, tag, GitHub prerelease.
4. The **`[release]` push** triggers another run: CI skipped, **deploy** runs again (version bump in packages), then **Promote next → main** after deploy succeeds.

GitHub Release and version bump happen **only after** a successful deploy, so tags are not ahead of what shipped.

Version changes only via that automated step on `next`. No manual bumping.

The `[release]` commit message prefix avoids re-running version-tag on the release commit itself.

